''Red Tail Reborn'' is described by [[Allmovie]] as "... the story of the brave African-American pilots who risked their lives in order to ensure that peace prevailed, and the people who have dedicated their lives to ensure that they are not forgotten."<ref name=RTRAM/> It tells three stories in one: the story of the Tuskegee Airmen, the history of the Red Tail Mustangs they flew (one of which is the subject of the restoration efforts) and the story of the late Don Hinz who crashed the first restored Mustang in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:DNWB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12C60A2E440AF920&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=<U+2018>Red Tail Reborn<U+2019> to air on PBS Feb. 14|accessdate=2010-01-25|date=2008-02-12|work=[[The Daily News (North Dakota)|The Daily News]]|author=Hevern, Erin C.}}</ref> 

The film sheds light on the bravery and heroism of the Tuskegee Airmen in their service as [[bomber]] escorts for the [[Allies of World War II|Allied Forces]] in the [[European Theatre of World War II]].<ref name=RTRAM>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/work/red-tail-reborn-471751|title=Red Tail Reborn|accessdate=2010-01-01|publisher=Macrovision Corporation|work=[[Allmovie]]}}</ref>  It documents that the Tuskegee Airmen were the country's first black military aviators taking flight in World War II, despite contemporary stereotyping of black men as lacking the essential intellectual and emotional qualities necessary to fly. The film even presents government documents deriding black men as substandard and "cowards". It describes segregation endured by the black military officers, and it describes how these pilots distinguished themselves with their record.<ref name=SoTAtaoP/>

It details the evolution of the Red Tail Project mission and the re-dedication to this enthusiasm when the mission's leader perished while flying a plane in homage to the Tuskegee Airmen.<ref name=RTRAM/>  This includes an explanation of the provenance of the plane and the various restoration efforts that led up to the Red Tail Project.<ref name=RTR>''Red Tail Reborn'', 2007, Hemlock Films.</ref>

==History and production==
Several of the Tuskegee Airmen were from the northeast Ohio region.  Among those that Cleveland filmmaker White interviewed to make the film were 13 of the Tuskegee airmen.<ref name=SoTAtaoP>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:RCOC&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=1249C9E31EB73860&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Story of Tuskegee Airmen to air on PBS|accessdate=2010-01-01|date=2008-02-05|work=[[The Repository]]|author=Goshay, Charita M.}}</ref>  One of these veterans interviewed was WWII, [[Korean War]] and [[Vietnam War]] veteran Col. Charles McGee, whom White said had more combat flight hours than any American.<ref name=SoTAtaoP/>  The film was shot in {{USCity|Billings|Montana}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0795451/trivia|title=Trivia for Red Tail Reborn (2007)|accessdate=2009-12-31|publisher=[[IMDb.com]]}}</ref>  The film was produced to help increase awareness and elicit financial support for The Red Tail Project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:PVPB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=122C82194515A2C0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Red Tail Project takes flight again|accessdate=2010-01-01|date=2008-08-22|author=Doss, Robert|work=[[Palos Verdes Peninsula News]]}}</ref> The film was produced by Cleveland-based Hemlock Films, which is White's production company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hemlockfilms.com/html/news___links.html|title=Film Maker To Speak At Aviation Hall Of Fame Dec. 17TH Event|accessdate=2010-03-21|publisher=Hemlock Films}}</ref> It was underwritten by the [[Parker Hannifin|Parker Hannifin Corporation]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://westernreservepublicmedia.org/images/presreport_winter08.pdf |title=Western Reserve Public Media |accessdate=March 21, 2010 |format=PDF}}</ref>


The film was inspired while White was filming ''[[The Restorers]]'', after a [[P-51 Mustang|P-51C Mustang]] landed for refueling and White met Doug Rozendaal, the pilot of the Red Tail Project's ''Tuskegee Airmen'' plane.  When White heard Don Hinz had been killed in a crash of that very same plane, he felt compelled to do a story focusing on it. Once he got involved in the project, a local PBS station committed to airing the final product, which was an early step in the successful development of the project.  When researching the film he noticed a lack of resources about the Tuskegee Airmen and felt driven to fill the void.<ref name=RTRPBS/>

==Airings and DVD release==
The film by White was premiered at the [[MAPS Air Museum]] at the [[Akron-Canton Regional Airport]] in {{USCity|Green|Ohio}} on Saturday February 10, 2007 and debuted during a [[simulcast]] on [[Western Reserve Public Media]], PBS network stations serving northeastern Ohio, the following day.<ref name=RTRpaam>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuskegeeairmen.org/uploads/RedTailReborn.pdf|title=<U+201C>Red Tail Reborn<U+201D> premieres at air museum|accessdate=2009-12-31|date=2007-02-11|work=[[The Repository]]|author=Monsewicz, Lisa}}</ref>  The stations reaired the show four more times between February 13 and February 20.<ref name=RTRpaam/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CPDB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=1173AA0F73270C08&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Contract issues led Monday away from Channel 3|accessdate=2009-12-31|date=2007-02-10|work=[[The Plain Dealer]]|author=Washington, Julie E.|page=E1}}</ref>  The film debuted in western Ohio at [[Wright State University]] on March 22, 2007 at which time a two-disc DVD was made available.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:DDNB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=118015EBB772DAD0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=WSU Graduate's Tuskegee Airmen Documentary To Get Dayton Launch|accessdate=2009-12-31|date=2007-03-16|work=[[Dayton Daily News]]|author=Larsen, Dave|page=GO29}}</ref>  It was released to the general public in DVD format on March 23, 2007.<ref name=RTR(2)>{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.com/Reborn-Pilots-332nd-Fighter-Group/dp/B000O78THK|title=Red Tail Reborn (2008)|accessdate=2009-12-31|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]}}</ref>  The film, which was [[Motion picture rating system|not rated]], was available in 1.33:1 [[aspect ratio]] and in Color, [[Dolby]], DVD, [[NTSC]], [[widescreen]] format.<ref name=RTR(2)/> was produced in color format. The film began national PBS broadcasts in during [[Black History Month]] in February 2008, reaching over 300 affiliates in its initial national airing,<ref name=FotRTrtD/> although specific dates and times varied from station to station.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:USTB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=11EB33EDCE9137B0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=TV offers lots of programming related to Black History Month|accessdate=2010-01-01|date=2008-02-06|work=[[USA Today]]|author=Hughes, Mike}}</ref>  The PBS airings began on February 5.<ref name=RTRPBS>{{cite web|url=http://www.pbs.org/redtailreborn/|title=Red Tail Reborn|publisher=[[Public Broadcasting Service]]/Hemlock Films|accessdate=2010-01-01}}</ref>  PBS also aired the film later in 2008 during its November [[Veterans Day]] programming.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ARMB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=1248B1132BAB3300&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Monthlong TV tribute to veterans|accessdate=2010-01-01|date=2008-11-10|page=42|work=[[Army Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:MTMB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=124906E495D176E8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Monthlong TV tribute to veterans|accessdate=2010-01-01|date=2008-11-10|page=42|work=[[Marine Corps Times]]}}</ref>

The DVD release includes a second disc with four hours of additional interviews, deleted scenes, and productions stills. A reviewer from ''[[Flight Journal]]'', feels the DVD package will connect with an audience of actual and aspiring restorers of military combat aircraft, which sometimes referred to as warbirds.  It notes that the narrator, Michael Dorn, is a warbird owner and pilot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redtailreborn.com/html/reviews.html|title=Flight Journal|author=Farmer, James|accessdate=2010-01-01}}</ref>

==Legacy==
In 2008, the film garnered three regional [[Emmy Award]]s from the Lower Great Lakes Region of the [[National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]] in the following categories: Best Informational/Instructional Program, Best Music Composition/ Arrangement and Best Research.<ref name=FotRTrtD>{{cite web|url=http://www.generalaviationnews.com/?p=15740|title=<U+2018>Flight of the Red Tail<U+2019> released to DVD|accessdate=2009-12-31|date=2009-11-29|author=Wood, Janice|work=[[General Aviation News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nataslgl.org/home.htm?emmy_winners_08.html~mainFrame|title=2008 Emmy Award Winners|accessdate=2009-12-31|date=|publisher=NATAS Lower Great Lakes Chapter}}</ref>  The film had been nominated for a total of six Emmys including the following additional categories: Best Lighting Location, Best Videographer - Program (Non News), Best Writer - Program (Non-News).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nataslgl.org/images/Nominations%20-%20as%20presented%208-13.pdf|title=Cleveland Regional Emmy Award Nominations|accessdate=2010-01-01|publisher=[[National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]] - Lower Great Lakes Chapter}}</ref>  The 2004 film followed the success of ''The Restorers'', which chronicled the restoration efforts for various warbird and vintage aircraft and which also won regional Emmy Award recognition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.therestorers.com/html/news.html|title=The Restorers: Giving History A Future: News|accessdate=2010-01-01|publisher=Hemlock Films}}</ref><ref name=SoTAtaoP/>  Whereas, ''The Restorers'' focuses on general aircraft restoration,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/work/the-restorers-290083|title=The Restorers|accessdate=2010-01-01|work=[[Allmovie]]}}</ref> the ''Red Tail Reborn'' expounds upon the restoration and rebuilding of a specific  plane and the Red Tail Project.  Although it was not released in theatres and its DVD sales where not among the top 100 in 2007,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/dvd/charts/annual/2007.php|title=Top-Selling DVDs of 2007|accessdate=2010-03-21|publisher=Nash Information Services, LLC.}}</ref> the success of its national airing spawned a 2009 [[sequel]] entitled ''[[Flight of the Red Tail]]'', which is also known as ''Red Tail Reborn 2'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1233345/|title=Flight of the Red Tail (2009)|accessdate=2009-12-31|publisher=[[IMDb.com]]}}</ref> that was available on DVD on November 27.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:SNSB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12BA1E688C032E18&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|title=Wright State grad to speak at Dec. 17 aviation dinner|accessdate=2009-12-31|date=2009-10-28|work=[[Springfield News-Sun]]|author=}}</ref>  The sequel is a 12-minute documentary follow-up.<ref name=FotRTrtD/>

